<TITLE> RBI cuts repo rate by 50 bps </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, Nov 01 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) on Saturday unexpectedly cut its repo rate or main short-term lending rate by 50 basis points to 7.5 percent and banks' cash reserve requirements by 100 basis points to 5.5 percent. It also cut banks' bond reserve requirements by 1 percentage point to 24 percent of their deposits with effect from Nov 8, 2008, the RBI said in a notification posted on its website www.rbi.org.in. The cut in its repo rate will take effect from Nov. 3. The cut in banks' cash reserve requirements will take effect in two steps -- one from the fortnight beginning October. 25 and the second takes effect from November. 8 and will release 400 billion rupees ($81 billion) into the banking system. The move follows a 100 basis point cut in its main short-term lending rate last week and is the latest in a slew taken by policymakers to combat the spillover effects of a global financial crisis
